# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: essential-fatty-acid
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Algae are polyphyletic as they have multiple evolutionary origins.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Although algae with two-membraned chloroplasts seem to form a paraphyletic group within the clade Archaeplastida, other algae with chloroplasts that have three or more membranes evolved from protists that acquired photosynthesis after engulfing archaeplastids.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Most algae are single-celled organisms without roots, leaves, or stems.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Most are photoautotrophs and the main primary producers of aquatic ecosystems, although some are mixotrophs that derive metabolic energy both from internal photosynthesis and from foraging external nutrients.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Some unicellular algae have become heterotrophs or parasites, relying entirely on external energy sources.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Algae have photosynthetic machinery ultimately derived from cyanobacteria that produce oxygen by splitting water molecules, unlike photosynthetic bacteria.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Fossilized filamentous algae from the Vindhya basin have been dated to 1.6 to 1.7 billion years ago.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Because of the wide range of types of algae, there is a correspondingly wide range of industrial and traditional applications in human society.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Traditional seaweed farming practices have existed for thousands of years and have strong traditions in East Asian food cultures.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] More modern algaculture applications extend the food traditions for other applications, including cattle feed, using algae for bioremediation or pollution control, transforming sunlight into algae fuels or other chemicals used in industrial processes, and in medical and scientific applications.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The singular *alga* is the Latin word for "seaweed" and retains that meaning in English.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Although some speculate that it is related to Latin *algēre*, "be cold", no reason is known to associate seaweed with temperature.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] A more likely source is *alliga*, "binding, entwining".
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The Ancient Greek word for "seaweed" was φῦκος (*phŷkos*), which could mean either the seaweed (probably red algae) or a red dye derived from it.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The Latinization, *fūcus*, meant primarily the cosmetic rouge.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The etymology is uncertain, but a strong candidate has long been some word related to the Biblical פוך (*pūk*), "paint" (if not that word itself), a cosmetic eye-shadow used by the Ancient Egyptians and other inhabitants of the eastern Mediterranean.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] It could be any color: black, red, green, or blue.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The study of algae is most commonly called phycology (from Greek *phykos* 'seaweed'); the term algology is falling out of use.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The algae are a heterogeneous group of mostly photosynthetic organisms that produce oxygen and lack the reproductive features and structural complexity of land plants.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] This concept includes the cyanobacteria, which are prokaryotes, and all photosynthetic protists, which are eukaryotes.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] They contain chlorophyll *a* as their primary photosynthetic pigment, and generally inhabit aquatic environments.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] However, there are many exceptions to this definition.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Many non-photosynthetic protists are included in the study of algae, such as the heterotrophic relatives of euglenophytes or the numerous species of colorless algae that have lost their chlorophyll during evolution (e.g., *Prototheca*).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Some exceptional species of algae tolerate dry terrestrial habitats, such as soil, rocks, or caves hidden from light sources, although they still need enough moisture to become active.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] A range of algal morphologies is exhibited, and convergence of features in unrelated groups is common.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The only groups to exhibit three-dimensional multicellular thalli are the reds and browns, and some chlorophytes.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Apical growth is constrained to subsets of these groups: the florideophyte reds, various browns, and the charophytes.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The form of charophytes is quite different from those of reds and browns, because they have distinct nodes, separated by internode 'stems'; whorls of branches reminiscent of the horsetails occur at the nodes.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Conceptacles are another polyphyletic trait; they appear in the coralline algae and the Hildenbrandiales, as well as the browns.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Most of the simpler algae are unicellular flagellates or amoeboids, but colonial and nonmotile forms have developed independently among several of the groups.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] In three lines, even higher levels of organization have been reached, with full tissue differentiation.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] These are the brown algae,—some of which may reach 50 m in length (kelps)—the red algae, and the green algae.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The most complex forms are found among the charophyte algae (see Charales and Charophyta), in a lineage that eventually led to the higher land plants.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The innovation that defines these nonalgal plants is the presence of female reproductive organs with protective cell layers that protect the zygote and developing embryo.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Hence, the land plants are referred to as the Embryophytes.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The term algal turf is commonly used but poorly defined.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Algal turfs are thick, carpet-like beds of seaweed that retain sediment and compete with foundation species like corals and kelps, and they are usually less than 15 cm tall.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Such a turf may consist of one or more species, and will generally cover an area in the order of a square metre or more.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Many algae, particularly species of the Characeae, have served as model experimental organisms to understand the mechanisms of the water permeability of membranes, osmoregulation, salt tolerance, cytoplasmic streaming, and the generation of action potentials.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Plant hormones are found not only in higher plants, but in algae, too.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Rhodophyta, Chlorophyta, and Heterokontophyta, the three main algal divisions, have life cycles which show considerable variation and complexity.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] In general, an asexual phase exists where the seaweed's cells are diploid, a sexual phase where the cells are haploid, followed by fusion of the male and female gametes.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Asexual reproduction permits efficient population increases, but less variation is possible.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Commonly, in sexual reproduction of unicellular and colonial algae, two specialized, sexually compatible, haploid gametes make physical contact and fuse to form a zygote.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] To ensure a successful mating, the development and release of gametes is highly synchronized and regulated; pheromones may play a key role in these processes.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Sexual reproduction allows for more variation and provides the benefit of efficient recombinational repair of DNA damage during meiosis, a key stage of the sexual cycle.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] However, sexual reproduction is more costly than asexual reproduction.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Meiosis has been shown to occur in many different species of algae.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Linnaeus, in *Species Plantarum* (1753), the starting point for modern botanical nomenclature, recognized 14 genera of algae, of which only four are currently considered among algae.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] In *Systema Naturae*, Linnaeus described the genera *Volvox* and *Corallina*, and a species of *Acetabularia* (as *Madrepora*), among the animals.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] In 1768, Samuel Gottlieb Gmelin (1744–1774) published the *Historia Fucorum*, the first work dedicated to marine algae and the first book on marine biology to use the then new binomial nomenclature of Linnaeus.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] It included elaborate illustrations of seaweed and marine algae on folded leaves.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Harvey (1811–1866) and Lamouroux (1813) were the first to divide macroscopic algae into four divisions based on their pigmentation.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] This is the first use of a biochemical criterion in plant systematics.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Harvey's four divisions are: red algae (Rhodospermae), brown algae (Melanospermae), green algae (Chlorospermae), and Diatomaceae.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] At this time, microscopic algae were discovered and reported by a different group of workers (e.g., O.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Müller and Ehrenberg) studying the Infusoria (microscopic organisms).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Unlike macroalgae, which were clearly viewed as plants, microalgae were frequently considered animals because they are often motile.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Even the nonmotile (coccoid) microalgae were sometimes merely seen as stages of the lifecycle of plants, macroalgae, or animals.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Although used as a taxonomic category in some pre-Darwinian classifications, e.g., Linnaeus (1753), de Jussieu (1789), Lamouroux (1813), Harvey (1836), Horaninow (1843), Agassiz (1859), Wilson & Cassin (1864), in further classifications, the "algae" are seen as an artificial, polyphyletic group.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Throughout the 20th century, most classifications treated the following groups as divisions or classes of algae: cyanophytes, rhodophytes, chrysophytes, xanthophytes, bacillariophytes, phaeophytes, pyrrhophytes (cryptophytes and dinophytes), euglenophytes, and chlorophytes.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] With the abandonment of plant-animal dichotomous classification, most groups of algae (sometimes all) were included in Protista, later also abandoned in favour of Eukaryota.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] However, as a legacy of the older plant life scheme, some groups that were also treated as protozoans in the past still have duplicated classifications (see ambiregnal protists).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] In other cases, some groups were originally characterized as parasitic algae (e.g., *Chlorochytrium*), but later were seen as endophytic algae.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Some filamentous bacteria (e.g., *Beggiatoa*) were originally seen as algae.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Furthermore, groups like the apicomplexans are also parasites derived from ancestors that possessed plastids, but are not included in any group traditionally seen as algae.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The most recent estimate (as of January 2024) documents 50,605 living and 10,556 fossil algal species, according to the online database AlgaeBase.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] They are classified into 15 phyla or divisions.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Some phyla are not photosynthetic, namely Picophyta and Rhodelphidophyta, but they are included in the database due to their close relationship with red algae.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The various algal phyla can be differentiated according to several biological traits.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] They have distinct morphologies, photosynthetic pigmentation, storage products, cell wall composition, and mechanisms of carbon concentration.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Some phyla have unique cellular structures.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] , the most common genus of cyanobacteria.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Among prokaryotes, five major groups of bacteria have evolved the ability to photosynthesize, including heliobacteria, green sulfur and nonsulfur bacteria and proteobacteria.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] However, the only lineage where oxygenic photosynthesis has evolved is in the cyanobacteria, often known as blue-green algae for their blue-green (cyan) coloration.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] They are classified as the phylum Cyanobacteriota or Cyanophyta.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] However, this phylum also includes two classes of non-photosynthetic bacteria: Melainabacteria (also called Vampirovibrionia or Vampirovibrionophyceae) and Sericytochromatia (also known as Blackallbacteria).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] A third class contains the photosynthetic ones, known as Cyanophyceae (also called Cyanobacteriia or Oxyphotobacteria).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] As bacteria, their cells lack membrane-bound organelles, with the exception of thylakoids.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Like other algae, cyanobacteria have chlorophyll *a* as their primary photosynthetic pigment.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Their accessory pigments include phycobilins (phycoerythrobilin and phycocyanobilin), carotenoids and, in some cases, *b*, *d*, or *f* chlorophylls, generally distributed in phycobilisomes found in the surface of thylakoids.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] They display a variety of body forms, such as single cells, colonies, and unbranched or branched filaments.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Their cells are commonly covered in a sheath of mucilage, and they also have a typical gram-negative bacterial cell wall composed largely of peptidoglycan.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] They have various storage particles, including cyanophycin as aminoacid and nitrogen reserves, "cyanophycean starch" (similar to plant amylose) for carbohydrates, and lipid droplets.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Their Rubisco enzymes are concentrated in carboxysomes.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] They occupy a diverse array of aquatic and terrestrial habitats, including extreme environments from hot springs to polar glaciers.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Some are subterranean, living via hydrogen-based lithoautotrophy instead of photosynthesis.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Three lineages of cyanobacteria, *Prochloraceae*, *Prochlorothrix* and *Prochlorococcus*, independently evolved to have chlorophylls *a* and *b* instead of phycobilisomes.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Due to their different pigmentation, they were historically grouped in a separate division, Prochlorophyta, as this is the typical pigmentation seen in green algae (e.g., chlorophytes).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Eventually, this classification became obsolete, as it is a polyphyletic grouping.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Cyanobacteria are included as algae by most phycological sources and by the International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants, although a few authors exclude them from the definition of algae and reserve the term for eukaryotes only.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Eukaryotic algae contain chloroplasts that are similar in structure to cyanobacteria.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Chloroplasts contain circular DNA like that in cyanobacteria and are interpreted as representing reduced endosymbiotic cyanobacteria.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] However, the exact origin of the chloroplasts is different among separate lineages of algae, reflecting their acquisition during different endosymbiotic events.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Many groups contain some members that are no longer photosynthetic.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Some retain plastids, but not chloroplasts, while others have lost plastids entirely.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Primary algae are those with "primary chloroplasts", i.e. chloroplasts with two membranes, evolved through a single symbiogenetic event with an endosymbiont β-cyanobacterium as early as 1.6 Gya during the Mesoproterozoic.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] These algae are mainly grouped in the clade Archaeplastida (meaning "ancient plastid"), which includes the major groups Viridiplantae (green algae *sensu lato* and all land plants) and Rhodophyta (red algae) as well as the minor group Glaucophyta (grey algae).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Land plants (embryophytes) are pigmented similarly to green algae and likely evolved from the freshwater green algae clade Streptophyta, which is sister taxon to Chlorophyta (green algae *sensu stricto*) and the basal clade Prasinodermophyta.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] There is also a minor group of amoeboid protists with primary plastids evolved via different origin and at a much later date than archaeplastid chloroplasts.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The four species of the euglyphid amoebae genus *Paulinella*, have cyanobionts (known as cyanelles) that perform photosynthesis, likely originated from the endosymbiosis of a α-cyanobacterium (probably an ancestral member of Chroococcales), about 90–140 Mya during the Cretaceous.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Secondary algae are eukaryotes with "secondary chloroplasts", i.e. those evolved from phagocytosis and subsequent endosymbiosis of primary algae (mainly green or red algae) or other secondary algae, thus "stealing" the endosymbionts' photosynthetic capability.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] As a result, these algae have chloroplasts surrounded by three or more membranes, and appeared independently in various distantly related protist lineages.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Two lineages of secondary algae, chlorarachniophytes and euglenophytes have "green" chloroplasts containing chlorophylls *a* and *b*.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Their chloroplasts are surrounded by four and three membranes, respectively, and were probably retained from ingested green algae.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Other groups have "red" chloroplasts containing chlorophylls *a* and *c*, and phycobilins.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The shape can vary; they may be of discoid, plate-like, reticulate, cup-shaped, spiral, or ribbon shaped.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] They have one or more pyrenoids to preserve protein and starch.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The latter chlorophyll type is not known from any prokaryotes or primary chloroplasts, but genetic similarities with red algae suggest a relationship there.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The typical dinoflagellate chloroplast has three membranes, but considerable diversity exists in chloroplasts within the group, and a number of endosymbiotic events apparently occurred.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The Apicomplexa, a group of closely related parasites, also have plastids called apicoplasts, which are not photosynthetic.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The Chromerida are the closest relatives of apicomplexans, and some have retained their chloroplasts.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The three alveolate groups evolved from a common myzozoan ancestor that obtained chloroplasts.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The distribution of algal species has been fairly well studied since the founding of phytogeography in the mid-19th century.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Algae spread mainly by the dispersal of spores analogously to the dispersal of cryptogamic plants by spores.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Spores can be found in a variety of environments: fresh and marine waters, air, soil, and in or on other organisms.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Whether a spore is to grow into an adult organism depends on the species and the environmental conditions where the spore lands.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The spores of freshwater algae are dispersed mainly by running water and wind, as well as by living carriers.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] However, not all bodies of water can carry all species of algae, as the chemical composition of certain water bodies limits the algae that can survive within them.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Marine spores are often spread by ocean currents.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Ocean water presents many vastly different habitats based on temperature and nutrient availability, resulting in phytogeographic zones, regions, and provinces.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] To some degree, the distribution of algae is subject to floristic discontinuities caused by geographical features, such as Antarctica, long distances of ocean or general land masses.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] It is, therefore, possible to identify species occurring by locality, such as "Pacific algae" or "North Sea algae".
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] When they occur out of their localities, hypothesizing a transport mechanism is usually possible, such as the hulls of ships.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] For example, *Ulva reticulata* and *U. fasciata* travelled from the mainland to Hawaii in this manner.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Mapping is possible for select species only: "there are many valid examples of confined distribution patterns." For example, *Clathromorphum* is an arctic genus and is not mapped far south of there.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] For example, according to one standard textbook, in the British Isles, the *UK Biodiversity Steering Group Report* estimated there to be 20,000 algal species in the UK.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Another checklist reports only about 5,000 species.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] and so on, but lacking any scientific basis or reliable sources, these numbers have no more credibility than the British ones mentioned above.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Most estimates also omit microscopic algae, such as phytoplankton.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Algae are prominent in bodies of water, common in terrestrial environments, and are found in unusual environments, such as on snow and ice.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Seaweeds grow mostly in shallow marine waters, less than 100 m (330 ft) deep; however, some such as *Navicula pennata* have been recorded to a depth of 360 m (1,180 ft).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] A type of algae, *Ancylonema nordenskioeldii*, was found in Greenland in areas known as the 'Dark Zone', which caused an increase in the rate of melting ice sheet.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The same algae was found in the Italian Alps, after pink ice appeared on parts of the Presena glacier.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The various sorts of algae play significant roles in aquatic ecology.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Microscopic forms that live suspended in the water column (phytoplankton) provide the food base for most marine food chains.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] In very high densities (algal blooms), these algae may discolor the water and outcompete, poison, or asphyxiate other life forms.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Algae can be used as indicator organisms to monitor pollution in various aquatic systems.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] In many cases, algal metabolism is sensitive to various pollutants.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Due to this, the species composition of algal populations may shift in the presence of chemical pollutants.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] To detect these changes, algae can be sampled from the environment and maintained in laboratories with relative ease.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Some species of algae form symbiotic relationships with other organisms.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] In these symbioses, the algae supply photosynthates (organic substances) to the host organism providing protection to the algal cells.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The host organism derives some or all of its energy requirements from the algae.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Lichens are defined by the International Association for Lichenology to be "an association of a fungus and a photosynthetic symbiont resulting in a stable vegetative body having a specific structure".
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The fungi, or mycobionts, are mainly from the Ascomycota with a few from the Basidiomycota.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] In nature, they do not occur separate from lichens.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] It is unknown when they began to associate.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] One or more mycobiont associates with the same phycobiont species, from the green algae, except that alternatively, the mycobiont may associate with a species of cyanobacteria (hence "photobiont" is the more accurate term).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] A photobiont may be associated with many different mycobionts or may live independently; accordingly, lichens are named and classified as fungal species.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The association is termed a morphogenesis because the lichen has a form and capabilities not possessed by the symbiont species alone (they can be experimentally isolated).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The photobiont possibly triggers otherwise latent genes in the mycobiont.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Trentepohlia is an example of a common green alga genus worldwide that can grow on its own or be lichenised.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Lichen thus share some of the habitat and often similar appearance with specialized species of algae (*aerophytes*) growing on exposed surfaces such as tree trunks and rocks and sometimes discoloring them.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Coral reefs are accumulated from the calcareous exoskeletons of marine invertebrates of the order Scleractinia (stony corals).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] These animals metabolize sugar and oxygen to obtain energy for their cell-building processes, including secretion of the exoskeleton, with water and carbon dioxide as byproducts.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Dinoflagellates (algal protists) are often endosymbionts in the cells of the coral-forming marine invertebrates, where they accelerate host-cell metabolism by generating sugar and oxygen immediately available through photosynthesis using incident light and the carbon dioxide produced by the host.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Reef-building stony corals (hermatypic corals) require endosymbiotic algae from the genus *Symbiodinium* to be in a healthy condition.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The loss of *Symbiodinium* from the host is known as coral bleaching, a condition which leads to the deterioration of a reef.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Endosymbiontic green algae live close to the surface of some sponges, for example, breadcrumb sponges (*Halichondria panicea*).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The alga is thus protected from predators; the sponge is provided with oxygen and sugars which can account for 50 to 80% of sponge growth in some species.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Prokaryotic algae, i.e., cyanobacteria, are the only group of organisms where oxygenic photosynthesis has evolved.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The oldest undisputed fossil evidence of cyanobacteria is dated at 2100 million years ago, although stromatolites, associated with cyanobacterial biofilms, appear as early as 3500 million years ago in the fossil record.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Eukaryotic algae are polyphyletic thus their origin cannot be traced back to a single hypothetical common ancestor.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] It is thought that they came into existence when photosynthetic coccoid cyanobacteria got phagocytized by a unicellular heterotrophic eukaryote (a protist), giving rise to double-membranous primary plastids.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Such symbiogenic events (primary symbiogenesis) are believed to have occurred more than 1.5 billion years ago during the Calymmian period, early in Boring Billion, but it is difficult to track the key events because of so much time gap.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] This process of serial cell "capture" and "enslavement" explains the diversity of photosynthetic eukaryotes.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The oldest undisputed fossil evidence of eukaryotic algae is *Bangiomorpha pubescens*, a red alga found in rocks around 1047 million years old.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Recent genomic and phylogenomic approaches have significantly clarified plastid genome evolution, the horizontal movement of endosymbiont genes to the "host" nuclear genome, and plastid spread throughout the eukaryotic tree of life.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] It is accepted that both euglenophytes and chlorarachniophytes obtained their chloroplasts from chlorophytes that became endosymbionts.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] In particular, euglenophyte chloroplasts share the most resemblance with the genus *Pyramimonas*.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] However, there is still no clear order in which the secondary and tertiary endosymbioses occurred for the "chromist" lineages (ochrophytes, cryptophytes, haptophytes and myzozoans).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Two main models have been proposed to explain the order, both of which agree that cryptophytes obtained their chloroplasts from red algae.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] One model, hypothesized in 2014 by John W.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Stiller and coauthors, suggests that a cryptophyte became the plastid of ochrophytes, which in turn became the plastid of myzozoans and haptophytes.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The other model, suggested by Andrzej Bodył and coauthors in 2009, describes that a cryptophyte became the plastid of both haptophytes and ochrophytes, and it is a haptophyte that became the plastid of myzozoans instead.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] These charophyte algae probably already developed filamentous thalli and holdfasts that superficially resembled plant stems and roots, and probably had an isomorphic alternation of generations.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] They perhaps evolved some 850 mya and might even be as early as 1 Gya during the late phase of the Boring Billion.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Algaculture is a form of aquaculture involving the farming of species of algae.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The majority of algae that are intentionally cultivated fall into the category of microalgae (also referred to as phytoplankton, microphytes, or planktonic algae).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Global production of farmed aquatic plants, overwhelmingly dominated by seaweeds, grew in output volume from 13.5 million tonnes in 1995, to just over 30 million tonnes in 2016 and 37.8 million tonnes in 2022 and 40 million tonnes in 2024.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] This increase was the result of production expansions led by China, followed by Malaysia, the Philippines, the United Republic of Tanzania, and the Russian Federation.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Cultured microalgae already contribute to a wide range of sectors in the emerging bioeconomy.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Research suggests there are large potentials and benefits of algaculture for the development of a future healthy and sustainable food system.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Seaweed farming or kelp farming is the practice of cultivating and harvesting seaweed.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] In its simplest form farmers gather from natural beds, while at the other extreme farmers fully control the crop's life cycle.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The seven most cultivated taxa are *Eucheuma* spp., *Kappaphycus alvarezii*, *Gracilaria* spp., *Saccharina japonica*, *Undaria pinnatifida*, *Pyropia* spp., and *Sargassum fusiforme*.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] *Eucheuma* and *K. alvarezii* are attractive for carrageenan (a gelling agent); *Gracilaria* is farmed for agar; the rest are eaten after limited processing.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Seaweeds are different from mangroves and seagrasses, as they are photosynthetic algal organisms and are non-flowering.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The largest seaweed-producing countries as of 2022 are China (58.62%) and Indonesia (28.6%); followed by South Korea (5.09%) and the Philippines (4.19%).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Seaweed farming has frequently been developed to improve economic conditions and to reduce fishing pressure.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) reported that world production in 2019 was over 35 million tonnes.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] North America produced some 23,000 tonnes of wet seaweed.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Alaska, Maine, France, and Norway each more than doubled their seaweed production since 2018*.* As of 2019, seaweed represented 30% of marine aquaculture.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] In 2023, the global seaweed extract market was valued at $16.5 billion, with strong projected growth.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Seaweed farming is a carbon negative crop, with a high potential for climate change mitigation.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The IPCC Special Report on the Ocean and Cryosphere in a Changing Climate recommends "further research attention" as a mitigation tactic.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] World Wildlife Fund, Oceans 2050, and The Nature Conservancy publicly support expanded seaweed cultivation.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] An algae bioreactor is used for cultivating micro or macroalgae.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Algae may be cultivated for the purposes of biomass production (as in a seaweed cultivator), wastewater treatment, CO2 fixation, or aquarium/pond filtration in the form of an algae scrubber.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Algae bioreactors vary widely in design, falling broadly into two categories: open reactors and enclosed reactors.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Open reactors are exposed to the atmosphere while enclosed reactors, also commonly called photobioreactors, are isolated to varying extents from the atmosphere.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Specifically, algae bioreactors can be used to produce fuels such as biodiesel and bioethanol, to generate animal feed, or to reduce pollutants such as NOx and CO2 in flue gases of power plants.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Fundamentally, this kind of bioreactor is based on the photosynthetic reaction, which is performed by the chlorophyll-containing algae itself using dissolved carbon dioxide and sunlight.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The carbon dioxide is dispersed into the reactor fluid to make it accessible to the algae.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The bioreactor has to be made out of transparent material.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] To be competitive and independent from fluctuating support from (local) policy on the long run, biofuels should equal or beat the cost level of fossil fuels.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Here, algae-based fuels hold great promise, directly related to the potential to produce more biomass per unit area in a year than any other form of biomass.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The break-even point for algae-based biofuels is estimated to occur by 2025.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Today, algae are used by humans in many ways; for example, as fertilizers, soil conditioners, and livestock feed.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Aquatic and microscopic species are cultured in clear tanks or ponds and are either harvested or used to treat effluents pumped through the ponds.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Algaculture on a large scale is an important type of aquaculture in some places.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Maerl is commonly used as a soil conditioner.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Algae are used as foods in many countries: China consumes more than 70 species, including *fat choy*, a cyanobacterium considered a vegetable; Japan, over 20 species such as *nori* and *aonori*; Ireland, dulse; Chile, cochayuyo.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Laver is used to make laverbread in Wales, where it is known as *bara lawr*.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] In Korea, green laver is used to make *gim*.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The oils from some algae have high levels of unsaturated fatty acids.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Some varieties of algae favored by vegetarianism and veganism contain the long-chain, essential omega-3 fatty acids, docosahexaenoic acid (DHA) and eicosapentaenoic acid (EPA).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Fish oil contains the omega-3 fatty acids, but the original source is algae (microalgae in particular), which are eaten by marine life such as copepods and are passed up the food chain.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The natural pigments (carotenoids and chlorophylls) produced by algae can be used as alternatives to chemical dyes and coloring agents.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Carrageenan, from the red alga *Chondrus crispus*, is used as a thickener and stabilizer in milk products.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Agar, a gelatinous substance derived from red algae, has a number of commercial uses.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] It is a good medium on which to grow bacteria and fungi, as most microorganisms cannot digest agar.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Alginic acid, or alginate, is extracted from brown algae.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Its uses range from gelling agents in food, to medical dressings.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Alginic acid also has been used in the field of biotechnology as a biocompatible medium for cell encapsulation and cell immobilization.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Molecular cuisine is also a user of the substance for its gelling properties, by which it becomes a delivery vehicle for flavours.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Between 100,000 and 170,000 wet tons of *Macrocystis* are harvested annually in New Mexico for alginate extraction and abalone feed.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Agricultural Research Service scientists found that 60–90% of nitrogen runoff and 70–100% of phosphorus runoff can be captured from manure effluents using a horizontal algae scrubber, also called an algal turf scrubber (ATS).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Scientists developed the ATS, which consists of shallow, 30-metre (100 ft) raceways of nylon netting where algae colonies can form, and studied its efficacy for three years.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] They found that algae can readily be used to reduce the nutrient runoff from agricultural fields and increase the quality of water flowing into rivers, streams, and oceans.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Researchers collected and dried the nutrient-rich algae from the ATS and studied its potential as an organic fertilizer.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] They found that cucumber and corn seedlings grew just as well using ATS organic fertilizer as they did with commercial fertilizers.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Algae scrubbers, using bubbling upflow or vertical waterfall versions, are now also being used to filter aquaria and ponds.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The alga *Stichococcus bacillaris* has been seen to colonize silicone resins used at archaeological sites; biodegrading the synthetic substance.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Various polymers can be created from algae, which can be especially useful in the creation of bioplastics.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] These include hybrid plastics, cellulose-based plastics, poly-lactic acid, and bio-polyethylene.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Several companies have begun to produce algae polymers commercially, including for use in flip-flops and in surf boards.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] Even algae is also used to prepare various polymeric resins suitable for coating applications.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/algae] The third island on Kunming Lake at Beijing's Summer Palace is called Zaojian Tang Dao (藻鑒堂島).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/aliphatic] In organic chemistry, hydrocarbons (compounds composed solely of carbon and hydrogen) are divided into two classes: aromatic compounds and **aliphatic compounds** (/ˌælɪˈfætɪk/; G.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/aliphatic] Aliphatic compounds can be saturated (in which all the C-C bonds are single, requiring the structure to be completed, or 'saturated', by hydrogen) like hexane, or unsaturated, like hexene and hexyne.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/aliphatic] Open-chain compounds, whether straight or branched, and which contain no rings of any type, are always aliphatic.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/aliphatic] Cyclic compounds can be aliphatic if they are not aromatic.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/aliphatic] Aliphatic compounds can be saturated, joined by single bonds (alkanes), or unsaturated, with double bonds (alkenes) or triple bonds (alkynes).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/aliphatic] If other elements (heteroatoms) are bound to the carbon chain, the most common being oxygen, nitrogen, sulfur, and chlorine, it is no longer a hydrocarbon, and therefore no longer an aliphatic compound.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/aliphatic] However, such compounds may still be referred to as aliphatic if the hydrocarbon portion of the molecule is aliphatic, e.g. aliphatic amines, to differentiate them from aromatic amines.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/aliphatic] The least complex aliphatic compound is methane (CH4).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] In terms of its structure, it is named *all*-*cis*-9,12,15-octadecatrienoic acid.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] In physiological literature, it is listed by its lipid number, 18:3 (*n*−3).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] It is a carboxylic acid with an 18-carbon chain and three *cis* double bonds.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] The first double bond is located at the third carbon from the methyl end of the fatty acid chain, known as the *n* end.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] Thus, α-linolenic acid is a polyunsaturated *n*−3 (omega-3) fatty acid.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] It is a regioisomer of gamma-linolenic acid (GLA), an 18:3 (*n*−6) fatty acid (i.e., a polyunsaturated omega-6 fatty acid with three double bonds).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] The word *linolenic* is an irregular derivation from *linoleic*, which itself is derived from the Greek word *linon* (flax).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] *Oleic* means "of or relating to oleic acid" because saturating an omega-6 double bond of linoleic acid produces oleic acid.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] Similarly saturating one of linolenic acid's double bonds produces linoleic acid.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] Seed oils are the richest sources of α-linolenic acid, notably those of hempseed, chia, perilla, flaxseed (linseed oil), rapeseed (canola), and soybeans.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] Additionally, small amounts of α-linolenic acid can be obtained through the consumption of meats such as chicken.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] Some studies state that ALA remains stable during processing and cooking.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] However, other studies state that ALA might not be suitable for baking as it will polymerize with itself, a feature exploited in paint with transition metal catalysts.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] Some ALA may also oxidize at baking temperatures.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] ALA percentages in the table below refer to the oils extracted from each item.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] α-Linolenic acid is also obtained from the thylakoid membranes in the leaves of *Pisum sativum* (pea leaves).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] Plant chloroplasts consisting of more than 95 percent of photosynthetic thylakoid membranes are highly fluid due to the large abundance of ALA, evident as sharp resonances in high-resolution carbon-13 NMR spectra.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] α-Linolenic acid can be obtained by humans only through their diets.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] Humans lack the Δ-12 and Δ-15 desaturase enzymes required for processing stearic acid into A-linoleic acid or other unsaturated fatty acids.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] Dietary α-linolenic acid is metabolized to stearidonic acid, a precursor to a collection of polyunsaturated 20-, 22-, 24-, etc fatty acids (eicosatetraenoic acid, eicosapentaenoic acid, docosapentaenoic acid, tetracosapentaenoic acid, 6,9,12,15,18,21-tetracosahexaenoic acid, docosahexaenoic acid).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] Because the efficacy of *n*−3 long-chain polyunsaturated fatty acid (LC-PUFA) synthesis decreases down the cascade of α-linolenic acid conversion, DHA synthesis from α-linolenic acid is even more restricted than that of EPA.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] Conversion of ALA to DHA is higher in women than in men.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] This is likely due to the increased need for DHA in women in order to support a developing fetus and in producing breastmilk containing DHA.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] α-Linolenic acid is synthesized starting from stearic acid, which itself is synthesized through a general fatty acid synthesis pathway.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] Stearic acid is subsequently converted into oleic acid by Δ-9-desaturase.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] Then, oleic acid is converted into linoleic acid by Δ-12-desaturase.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] Finally, linoleic acid is converted into α-Linolenic acid by Δ-15-desaturase.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] Compared to many other oils, α-linolenic acid is more susceptible to oxidation.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] Oxidative instability of α-linolenic acid is one reason why producers choose to partially hydrogenate oils containing α-linolenic acid, such as soybean oil.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] Soybeans are the largest source of edible oils in the U.S., and, as of a 2007 study, 40% of soy oil production was partially hydrogenated.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] The source of susceptibility to oxidation in α-linolenic acid is presence of four bis-allylic hydrogen atoms.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] The Gibbs free energy of abstracting these hydrogens is uniquely low due to the potential for radical delocalization in the lipid radical product.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] This potential for delocalization confers a stabilizing effect that makes the overall oxidation pathway more favorable.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] Additionally, α-linolenic acid has four bis-allylic hydrogens compared to just 2 in linoleic acid, making abstraction more likely.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] Hydrogenation of ALA-containing fats can introduce trans fats.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] Consumers are increasingly avoiding products that contain trans fats, and governments have begun to ban trans fats in food products, including the US government as of May 2018.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] These regulations and market pressures have spurred the development of soybeans low in α-linolenic acid.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] These new soybean varieties yield a more stable oil that often do not require hydrogenation for many applications.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] ALA is an essential fatty acid, meaning consumption of ALA in the diet is required for human life, along with all other mammals.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] ALA consumption is associated with a lower risk of cardiovascular disease and a reduced risk of fatal coronary heart disease.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] Dietary ALA intake can improve lipid profiles by decreasing triglycerides, total cholesterol, high-density lipoprotein, and low-density lipoprotein.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] A 2021 review found that ALA intake is associated with a reduced risk of mortality from all causes, cardiovascular disease, and coronary heart disease but a slightly higher risk of cancer mortality.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] In 1887, linolenic acid was discovered and named by the Austrian chemist Karl Hazura of the Imperial Technical Institute at Vienna (although he did not separate its isomers). α-Linolenic acid was first isolated in pure form in 1909 by Ernst Erdmann and F.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] Bedford of the University of Halle an der Saale, Germany, and by Adolf Rollett of the Universität Berlin, Germany, working independently, as cited in J.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] McCutcheon's synthesis in 1942, and referred to in Green and Hilditch's 1930s survey.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] It was first artificially synthesized in 1995 from C6 homologating agents.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/alpha-linolenic-acid] A Wittig reaction of the phosphonium salt of [(*Z-Z*)-nona-3,6-dien-1-yl]triphenylphosphonium bromide with methyl 9-oxononanoate, followed by saponification, completed the synthesis.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] Anandamide is derived from the non-oxidative metabolism of arachidonic acid, an essential omega-6 fatty acid.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] It is synthesized from *N*-arachidonoyl phosphatidylethanolamine by multiple pathways.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] It is degraded primarily by the fatty acid amide hydrolase (FAAH) enzyme, which converts anandamide into ethanolamine and arachidonic acid.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] As such, inhibitors of FAAH lead to elevated anandamide levels and are being pursued for possible therapeutic use.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] The discovery of anandamide was first reported in 1992 from laboratory studies in a pig brain and canine gut, becoming the first marijuana-like substance found in mammals.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] Its possible effects within the brain include the reward system, a broad topic resulting in many research studies.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] According to in vitro research, anandamide effects are mediated primarily by CB1 cannabinoid receptors in the central nervous system, and CB2 cannabinoid receptors in the periphery.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] The latter appear to be involved in functions of the immune system.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] Cannabinoid receptors were originally discovered as sensitive to Δ9-tetrahydrocannabinol (Δ9-THC, commonly called THC), which is the primary psychoactive cannabinoid found in cannabis.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] The discovery of anandamide came from research into CB1 and CB2, as it was inevitable that a naturally occurring (endogenous) chemical would be found to affect these receptors.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] Anandamide is under research for its potential involvement in the implantation of the early stage embryo in its blastocyst form into the uterus.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] Therefore, cannabinoids such as Δ9-THC might influence processes during the earliest stages of human pregnancy.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] Peak plasma anandamide occurs at ovulation and positively correlates with peak estradiol and gonadotrophin levels, suggesting that these may be involved in the regulation of anandamide levels.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] Subsequently, anandamide has been proposed as a biomarker of infertility, but so far lacks any predictive values in order to be used clinically.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] Both the CB1 and CB2 receptors (the binding site of anandamide) are under research for a possible role in positive and negative interpretation of environment and setting.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] The binding relationship of anandamide and the CB1/CB2 may affect neurotransmission of dopamine, serotonin, GABA, and glutamate.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] Endocannabinoids may disturb homeostasis in several ways: by enhancing hunger sensations, encouraging increased food intake, and shifting energy balance towards energy storage.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] A resultant decrease in energy expenditure is observed.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] Cortical glutamatergic transmission may be modulated by endocannabinoids during stress and fear habituation.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] Blockade of CB1 receptors was found to improve lipid resistance and lipid profile in obese subjects with type 2 diabetes.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] Elevated anandamide levels are found in people with nonalcoholic fatty liver disease, nonalcoholic steatohepatitis, and liver fibrosis.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] The American Academy of Dermatology has named topical anandamide a promising therapy for cutaneous lupus erythematosus.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] In humans, anandamide is biosynthesized from *N*-arachidonoyl phosphatidylethanolamine (NAPE).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] In turn, NAPE arises by transfer of arachidonic acid from lecithin to the free amine of cephalin through an *N*-acyltransferase enzyme.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] Anandamide synthesis from NAPE occurs via multiple pathways and includes enzymes such as phospholipase A2, phospholipase C and N-acetylphosphatidylethanolamine-hydrolysing phospholipase D (NAPE-PLD), with other key enzymes yet to be identified.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] Endogenous anandamide is present at very low levels and has a very short half-life due to the action of the enzyme fatty acid amide hydrolase (FAAH), which breaks it down into free arachidonic acid and ethanolamine.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] Studies of piglets show that dietary levels of arachidonic acid and other essential fatty acids affect the levels of anandamide and other endocannabinoids in the brain.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] High fat diet feeding in mice increases levels of anandamide in the liver and increases lipogenesis.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] Anandamide may be relevant to the development of obesity, at least in rodents.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] Paracetamol (known as acetaminophen in the US and Canada) is metabolically combined with arachidonic acid by FAAH to form AM404.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] This metabolite is a potent agonist at the TRPV1 vanilloid receptor, a weak agonist at both CB1 and CB2 receptors, and an inhibitor of anandamide reuptake.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] Consequently, anandamide levels in the body and brain are elevated.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] Thus, paracetamol acts as a pro-drug for a cannabimimetic metabolite, which may be partially or fully responsible for its analgesic effects.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] Black pepper contains the alkaloid guineesine, which is an anandamide reuptake inhibitor.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] It may therefore increase anandamide's physiological effects.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] Endocannabinoid transporters for anandamide and 2-arachidonoylglycerol include the heat shock proteins (Hsp70s) and fatty acid binding proteins (FABPs).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] Anandamide shows a preference for binding to cholesterol and ceramide over other membrane lipids.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] Cholesterol acts as a binding partner for anandamide.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] Initially, a hydrogen bond facilitates their interaction.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] Following this, anandamide is drawn towards the membrane interior, where it forms a molecular complex with cholesterol.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] This process involves a conformational adaptation of anandamide to the apolar membrane environment.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/anandamide] Subsequently, the anandamide-cholesterol complex is directed to the cannabinoid receptor (CB1) and then exits.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidic-acid] Its name derives from the Latin *arachis*—peanut.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidic-acid] It can be formed by the hydrogenation of arachidonic acid.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidic-acid] Reduction of arachidic acid yields arachidyl alcohol.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidic-acid] Arachidic acid is used for the production of detergents, photographic materials and lubricants.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidonic-acid] Together with omega−3 fatty acids and other omega−6 fatty acids, arachidonic acid provides energy for body functions, contributes to cell membrane structure, and participates in the synthesis of eicosanoids, which have numerous roles in physiology as signaling molecules.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidonic-acid] It was named after the similarly structured Arachidic acid, a constituent of peanut oil whose name in turn derives from the ancient Greek neologism *arachis* 'peanut'.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidonic-acid] Peanut oil does not contain any arachidonic acid, itself.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidonic-acid] **Arachidonate** is the name of the derived carboxylate anion (conjugate base of the acid), salts, and some esters.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidonic-acid] In chemical structure, arachidonic acid is a carboxylic acid with a 20-carbon chain and four *cis*-double bonds; the first double bond is located at the sixth carbon from the omega end.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidonic-acid] Some chemistry sources define 'arachidonic acid' to designate any of the eicosatetraenoic acids.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidonic-acid] However, almost all writings in biology, medicine, and nutrition limit the term to *all cis*-5,8,11,14-eicosatetraenoic acid.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidonic-acid] Arachidonic acid is a polyunsaturated fatty acid present in the phospholipids (especially phosphatidylethanolamine, phosphatidylcholine, and phosphatidylinositides) of membranes of the body's cells, and is abundant in the brain, muscles, and liver.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidonic-acid] Skeletal muscle is an especially active site of arachidonic acid retention, accounting for roughly 10–20% of the phospholipid fatty acid content typically.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidonic-acid] In addition to being involved in cellular signaling as a lipid second messenger involved in the regulation of signaling enzymes, such as PLC-γ, PLC-δ, and PKC-α, -β, and -γ isoforms, arachidonic acid is a key inflammatory intermediate and can also act as a vasodilator.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidonic-acid] Arachidonic acid is synthesized from linoleic acid (LA) via a process starting with the conversion of LA into gamma-linolenic acid (GLA), effected by Δ6 desaturase.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidonic-acid] Arachidonic acid is freed from phospholipids that contain an arachidonic acid sidechain by hydrolysis, catalyzed by the phospholipase A2 (PLA2).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidonic-acid] Arachidonic acid for signaling purposes appears to be derived by the action of group IVA cytosolic phospholipase A2 (cPLA2, 85 kDa), whereas inflammatory arachidonic acid is generated by the action of a low-molecular-weight secretory PLA2 (sPLA2, 14-18 kDa).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidonic-acid] The production of these derivatives and their actions in the body are collectively known as the "arachidonic acid cascade"; see Essential fatty acid interactions and the enzyme and metabolite linkages given in the previous paragraph for more details.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidonic-acid] Furthermore, any agent increasing intracellular calcium may cause activation of some forms of PLA2.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidonic-acid] Alternatively, arachidonic acid may be cleaved from phospholipids after phospholipase C (PLC) cleaves off the inositol trisphosphate group, yielding diacylglycerol (DAG), which subsequently is cleaved by DAG lipase to yield arachidonic acid.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidonic-acid] PLC may also be activated by MAP kinase.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidonic-acid] Activators of this pathway include PDGF and FGF.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidonic-acid] Along with other omega−6 and omega−3 fatty acids, arachidonic acid contributes to the structure of cell membranes.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidonic-acid] When incorporated into phospholipids, the omega fatty acid affects cell membrane properties, such as permeability and the activity of enzymes and cell-signaling mechanisms.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidonic-acid] Arachidonic acid, one of the most abundant fatty acids in the brain, is present in similar quantities to docosahexaenoic acid, with the two accounting for about 20% of brain fatty-acid content.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidonic-acid] Arachidonic acid is involved in the early neurological development of infants.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidonic-acid] Arachidonic acid is marketed as a dietary supplement.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidonic-acid] A 2019 review of clinical studies investigating the potential health effects of arachidonic acid supplementation of up to 1500 mg per day on human health found there were no clear benefits.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidonic-acid] There were no adverse effects in adults of using high daily doses (1500 mg) of arachidonic acid on several biomarkers of blood chemistry, immune function, and inflammation.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidonic-acid] A 2009 review indicated that consumption of 5−10% of food energy from omega−6 fatty acids including arachidonic acid may reduce the risk of cardiovascular diseases compared to lower intakes.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidonic-acid] A 2014 meta-analysis of possible associations between heart disease risk and individual fatty acids reported a significantly reduced risk of heart disease with higher levels of EPA, DHA, and arachidonic acid.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidonic-acid] Cats have low Δ6 desaturase activity and cannot efficiently convert linoleic acid into arachidonic acid.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/arachidonic-acid] As a result, they need to acquire it from food.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Elements of biosynthesis include: precursor compounds, chemical energy (e.g.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] ATP), and catalytic enzymes which may need coenzymes (e.g.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] These elements create monomers, the building blocks for macromolecules.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Some important biological macromolecules include: proteins, which are composed of amino acid monomers joined via peptide bonds, and DNA molecules, which are composed of nucleotides joined via phosphodiester bonds.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Biosynthesis occurs due to a series of chemical reactions.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Simple compounds that are converted into other compounds with the assistance of cofactors.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] For example, the synthesis of phospholipids requires acetyl CoA, while the synthesis of another membrane component, sphingolipids, requires NADH and FADH for the formation the sphingosine backbone.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Simple compounds that join to create a macromolecule.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] For example, fatty acids join to form phospholipids.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] In turn, phospholipids and cholesterol interact noncovalently in order to form the lipid bilayer.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Many intricate macromolecules are synthesized in a pattern of simple, repeated structures.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] For example, the simplest structures of lipids are fatty acids.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Fatty acids are hydrocarbon derivatives; they contain a carboxyl group "head" and a hydrocarbon chain "tail".
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] These fatty acids create larger components, which in turn incorporate noncovalent interactions to form the lipid bilayer.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Fatty acid chains are found in two major components of membrane lipids: phospholipids and sphingolipids.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] A third major membrane component, cholesterol, does not contain these fatty acid units.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The foundation of all biomembranes consists of a bilayer structure of phospholipids.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The phospholipid molecule is amphipathic; it contains a hydrophilic polar head and a hydrophobic nonpolar tail.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The phospholipid heads interact with each other and aqueous media, while the hydrocarbon tails orient themselves in the center, away from water.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] These latter interactions drive the bilayer structure that acts as a barrier for ions and molecules.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] There are various types of phospholipids; consequently, their synthesis pathways differ.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] However, the first step in phospholipid synthesis involves the formation of phosphatidate or diacylglycerol 3-phosphate at the endoplasmic reticulum and outer mitochondrial membrane.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The pathway starts with glycerol 3-phosphate, which gets converted to lysophosphatidate via the addition of a fatty acid chain provided by acyl coenzyme A.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Then, lysophosphatidate is converted to phosphatidate via the addition of another fatty acid chain contributed by a second acyl CoA; all of these steps are catalyzed by the glycerol phosphate acyltransferase enzyme.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Phospholipid synthesis continues in the endoplasmic reticulum, and the biosynthesis pathway diverges depending on the components of the particular phospholipid.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Like phospholipids, these fatty acid derivatives have a polar head and nonpolar tails.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Unlike phospholipids, sphingolipids have a sphingosine backbone.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Sphingolipids exist in eukaryotic cells and are particularly abundant in the central nervous system.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] For example, sphingomyelin is part of the myelin sheath of nerve fibers.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Sphingolipids are formed from ceramides that consist of a fatty acid chain attached to the amino group of a sphingosine backbone.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] These ceramides are synthesized from the acylation of sphingosine.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] As the image denotes, during sphingosine synthesis, palmitoyl CoA and serine undergo a condensation reaction which results in the formation of 3-dehydrosphinganine.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] This product is then reduced to form dihydrospingosine, which is converted to sphingosine via the oxidation reaction by FAD.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] This lipid belongs to a class of molecules called sterols.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Sterols have four fused rings and a hydroxyl group.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Cholesterol is a particularly important molecule.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Not only does it serve as a component of lipid membranes, it is also a precursor to several steroid hormones, including cortisol, testosterone, and estrogen.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Cholesterol is synthesized from acetyl CoA.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] More generally, this synthesis occurs in three stages, with the first stage taking place in the cytoplasm and the second and third stages occurring in the endoplasmic reticulum.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The biosynthesis of nucleotides involves enzyme-catalyzed reactions that convert substrates into more complex products.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Nucleotides are the building blocks of DNA and RNA.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Nucleotides are composed of a five-membered ring formed from ribose sugar in RNA, and deoxyribose sugar in DNA; these sugars are linked to a purine or pyrimidine base with a glycosidic bond and a phosphate group at the 5' location of the sugar.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The DNA nucleotides adenosine and guanosine consist of a purine base attached to a ribose sugar with a glycosidic bond.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] In the case of RNA nucleotides deoxyadenosine and deoxyguanosine, the purine bases are attached to a deoxyribose sugar with a glycosidic bond.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The purine bases on DNA and RNA nucleotides are synthesized in a twelve-step reaction mechanism present in most single-celled organisms.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Higher eukaryotes employ a similar reaction mechanism in ten reaction steps.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Purine bases are synthesized by converting phosphoribosyl pyrophosphate (PRPP) to inosine monophosphate (IMP), which is the first key intermediate in purine base biosynthesis.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Further enzymatic modification of IMP produces the adenosine and guanosine bases of nucleotides.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] GAR synthetase performs the condensation of activated glycine onto PRPP, forming glycineamide ribonucleotide (GAR).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] GAR transformylase adds a formyl group onto the amino group of GAR, forming formylglycinamide ribonucleotide (FGAR).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] FGAR amidotransferase catalyzes the addition of a nitrogen group to FGAR, forming formylglycinamidine ribonucleotide (FGAM).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] FGAM cyclase catalyzes ring closure, which involves removal of a water molecule, forming the 5-membered imidazole ring 5-aminoimidazole ribonucleotide (AIR).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] N5-CAIR synthetase transfers a carboxyl group, forming the intermediate N5-carboxyaminoimidazole ribonucleotide (N5-CAIR).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] N5-CAIR mutase rearranges the carboxyl functional group and transfers it onto the imidazole ring, forming carboxyamino- imidazole ribonucleotide (CAIR).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The two step mechanism of CAIR formation from AIR is mostly found in single celled organisms.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Higher eukaryotes contain the enzyme AIR carboxylase, which transfers a carboxyl group directly to AIR imidazole ring, forming CAIR.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] SAICAR synthetase forms a peptide bond between aspartate and the added carboxyl group of the imidazole ring, forming N-succinyl-5-aminoimidazole-4-carboxamide ribonucleotide (SAICAR).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] SAICAR lyase removes the carbon skeleton of the added aspartate, leaving the amino group and forming 5-aminoimidazole-4-carboxamide ribonucleotide (AICAR).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] AICAR transformylase transfers a carbonyl group to AICAR, forming N-formylaminoimidazole- 4-carboxamide ribonucleotide (FAICAR).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The final step involves the enzyme IMP synthase, which performs the purine ring closure and forms the inosine monophosphate intermediate.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Other DNA and RNA nucleotide bases that are linked to the ribose sugar via a glycosidic bond are thymine, cytosine and uracil (which is only found in RNA).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Uridine monophosphate biosynthesis involves an enzyme that is located in the mitochondrial inner membrane and multifunctional enzymes that are located in the cytosol.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Aspartate carbamoyltransferase condenses carbamoyl phosphate with aspartate to form uridosuccinate.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Dihydroorotase performs ring closure, a reaction that loses water, to form dihydroorotate.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Dihydroorotate dehydrogenase, located within the mitochondrial inner membrane, oxidizes dihydroorotate to orotate.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Orotate phosphoribosyl hydrolase (OMP pyrophosphorylase) condenses orotate with PRPP to form orotidine-5'-phosphate.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] OMP decarboxylase catalyzes the conversion of orotidine-5'-phosphate to UMP.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] After the uridine nucleotide base is synthesized, the other bases, cytosine and thymine are synthesized.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Cytosine biosynthesis is a two-step reaction which involves the conversion of UMP to UTP.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Phosphate addition to UMP is catalyzed by a kinase enzyme.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The enzyme CTP synthase catalyzes the next reaction step: the conversion of UTP to CTP by transferring an amino group from glutamine to uridine; this forms the cytosine base of CTP.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Cytosine is a nucleotide that is present in both DNA and RNA.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Therefore, after UTP is synthesized, it must be converted into a deoxy form to be incorporated into DNA.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] This conversion involves the enzyme ribonucleoside triphosphate reductase.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] This reaction that removes the 2'-OH of the ribose sugar to generate deoxyribose is not affected by the bases attached to the sugar.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] This non-specificity allows ribonucleoside triphosphate reductase to convert all nucleotide triphosphates to deoxyribonucleotide by a similar mechanism.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] In contrast to uracil, thymine bases are found mostly in DNA, not RNA.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Cells do not normally contain thymine bases that are linked to ribose sugars in RNA, thus indicating that cells only synthesize deoxyribose-linked thymine.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The enzyme thymidylate synthetase is responsible for synthesizing thymine residues from dUMP to dTMP.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] This reaction transfers a methyl group onto the uracil base of dUMP to generate dTMP.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The thymidylate synthase reaction, dUMP + 5,10-methylenetetrahydrofolate ⇔ dTMP + dihydrofolate, is shown to the right.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Although there are differences between eukaryotic and prokaryotic DNA synthesis, the following section denotes key characteristics of DNA replication shared by both organisms.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] DNA is composed of nucleotides that are joined by phosphodiester bonds.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] DNA synthesis, which takes place in the nucleus, is a semiconservative process, which means that the resulting DNA molecule contains an original strand from the parent structure and a new strand.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] DNA synthesis is catalyzed by a family of DNA polymerases that require four deoxynucleoside triphosphates, a template strand, and a primer with a free 3'OH in which to incorporate nucleotides.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] In order for DNA replication to occur, a replication fork is created by enzymes called helicases which unwind the DNA helix.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Topoisomerases at the replication fork remove supercoils caused by DNA unwinding, and single-stranded DNA binding proteins maintain the two single-stranded DNA templates stabilized prior to replication.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] DNA synthesis is initiated by the RNA polymerase primase, which makes an RNA primer with a free 3'OH.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] This primer is attached to the single-stranded DNA template, and DNA polymerase elongates the chain by incorporating nucleotides; DNA polymerase also proofreads the newly synthesized DNA strand.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Two types of strands are created simultaneously during replication: the leading strand, which is synthesized continuously and grows towards the replication fork, and the lagging strand, which is made discontinuously in Okazaki fragments and grows away from the replication fork.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Okazaki fragments are covalently joined by DNA ligase to form a continuous strand.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Then, to complete DNA replication, RNA primers are removed, and the resulting gaps are replaced with DNA and joined via DNA ligase.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] A protein is a polymer that is composed from amino acids that are linked by peptide bonds.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] There are more than 300 amino acids found in nature of which only twenty two, known as the proteinogenic amino acids, are the building blocks for protein.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Only green plants and most microbes are able to synthesize all of the 20 standard amino acids that are needed by all living species.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Mammals can only synthesize ten of the twenty standard amino acids.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The other amino acids, valine, methionine, leucine, isoleucine, phenylalanine, lysine, threonine and tryptophan for adults and histidine, and arginine for babies are obtained through diet.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The general structure of the standard amino acids includes a primary amino group, a carboxyl group and the functional group attached to the α-carbon.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The different amino acids are identified by the functional group.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] As a result of the three different groups attached to the α-carbon, amino acids are asymmetrical molecules.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] For all standard amino acids, except glycine, the α-carbon is a chiral center.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] In the case of glycine, the α-carbon has two hydrogen atoms, thus adding symmetry to this molecule.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] With the exception of proline, all of the amino acids found in life have the L-isoform conformation.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Proline has a functional group on the α-carbon that forms a ring with the amino group.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] One major step in amino acid biosynthesis involves incorporating a nitrogen group onto the α-carbon.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] In cells, there are two major pathways of incorporating nitrogen groups.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] One pathway involves the enzyme glutamine oxoglutarate aminotransferase (GOGAT) which removes the amide amino group of glutamine and transfers it onto 2-oxoglutarate, producing two glutamate molecules.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] In this catalysis reaction, glutamine serves as the nitrogen source.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] An image illustrating this reaction is found to the right.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The other pathway for incorporating nitrogen onto the α-carbon of amino acids involves the enzyme glutamate dehydrogenase (GDH).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] GDH is able to transfer ammonia onto 2-oxoglutarate and form glutamate.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Furthermore, the enzyme glutamine synthetase (GS) is able to transfer ammonia onto glutamate and synthesize glutamine, replenishing glutamine.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The glutamate family of amino acids includes the amino acids that derive from the amino acid glutamate.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] This family includes: glutamate, glutamine, proline, and arginine.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] This family also includes the amino acid lysine, which is derived from α-ketoglutarate.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The biosynthesis of glutamate and glutamine is a key step in the nitrogen assimilation discussed above.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The enzymes GOGAT and GDH catalyze the nitrogen assimilation reactions.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] In bacteria, the enzyme glutamate 5-kinase initiates the biosynthesis of proline by transferring a phosphate group from ATP onto glutamate.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The next reaction is catalyzed by the enzyme pyrroline-5-carboxylate synthase (P5CS), which catalyzes the reduction of the ϒ-carboxyl group of L-glutamate 5-phosphate.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] This results in the formation of glutamate semialdehyde, which spontaneously cyclizes to pyrroline-5-carboxylate.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Pyrroline-5-carboxylate is further reduced by the enzyme pyrroline-5-carboxylate reductase (P5CR) to yield a proline amino acid.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] In the first step of arginine biosynthesis in bacteria, glutamate is acetylated by transferring the acetyl group from acetyl-CoA at the N-α position; this prevents spontaneous cyclization.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The enzyme N-acetylglutamate synthase (glutamate N-acetyltransferase) is responsible for catalyzing the acetylation step.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Subsequent steps are catalyzed by the enzymes N-acetylglutamate kinase, N-acetyl-gamma-glutamyl-phosphate reductase, and acetylornithine/succinyldiamino pimelate aminotransferase and yield the N-acetyl-L-ornithine.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The acetyl group of acetylornithine is removed by the enzyme acetylornithinase (AO) or ornithine acetyltransferase (OAT), and this yields ornithine.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Then, the enzymes citrulline and argininosuccinate convert ornithine to arginine.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] There are two distinct lysine biosynthetic pathways: the diaminopimelic acid pathway and the α-aminoadipate pathway.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Aspartate semialdehyde dehydrogenase catalyzes the NADPH-dependent reduction of aspartyl phosphate to yield aspartate semialdehyde.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] 4-hydroxy-tetrahydrodipicolinate synthase adds a pyruvate group to the β-aspartyl-4-semialdehyde, and a water molecule is removed.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] This causes cyclization and gives rise to (2S,4S)-4-hydroxy-2,3,4,5-tetrahydrodipicolinate.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] 4-hydroxy-tetrahydrodipicolinate reductase catalyzes the reduction of (2S,4S)-4-hydroxy-2,3,4,5-tetrahydrodipicolinate by NADPH to yield Δ'-piperideine-2,6-dicarboxylate (2,3,4,5-tetrahydrodipicolinate) and H2O.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Tetrahydrodipicolinate acyltransferase catalyzes the acetylation reaction that results in ring opening and yields N-acetyl α-amino-ε-ketopimelate.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] N-succinyl-α-amino-ε-ketopimelate-glutamate aminotransaminase catalyzes the transamination reaction that removes the keto group of N-acetyl α-amino-ε-ketopimelate and replaces it with an amino group to yield N-succinyl-L-diaminopimelate.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] N-acyldiaminopimelate deacylase catalyzes the deacylation of N-succinyl-L-diaminopimelate to yield L,L-diaminopimelate.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] DAP epimerase catalyzes the conversion of L,L-diaminopimelate to the meso form of L,L-diaminopimelate.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] DAP decarboxylase catalyzes the removal of the carboxyl group, yielding L-lysine.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The serine family of amino acid includes: serine, cysteine, and glycine.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Most microorganisms and plants obtain the sulfur for synthesizing methionine from the amino acid cysteine.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Furthermore, the conversion of serine to glycine provides the carbons needed for the biosynthesis of the methionine and histidine.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] During serine biosynthesis, the enzyme phosphoglycerate dehydrogenase catalyzes the initial reaction that oxidizes 3-phospho-D-glycerate to yield 3-phosphonooxypyruvate.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The following reaction is catalyzed by the enzyme phosphoserine aminotransferase, which transfers an amino group from glutamate onto 3-phosphonooxypyruvate to yield L-phosphoserine.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The final step is catalyzed by the enzyme phosphoserine phosphatase, which dephosphorylates L-phosphoserine to yield L-serine.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] There are two known pathways for the biosynthesis of glycine.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Organisms that use ethanol and acetate as the major carbon source utilize the glyconeogenic pathway to synthesize glycine.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The other pathway of glycine biosynthesis is known as the glycolytic pathway.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] This pathway converts serine synthesized from the intermediates of glycolysis to glycine.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] In the glycolytic pathway, the enzyme serine hydroxymethyltransferase catalyzes the cleavage of serine to yield glycine and transfers the cleaved carbon group of serine onto tetrahydrofolate, forming 5,10-methylene-tetrahydrofolate.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Cysteine biosynthesis is a two-step reaction that involves the incorporation of inorganic sulfur.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] In microorganisms and plants, the enzyme serine acetyltransferase catalyzes the transfer of acetyl group from acetyl-CoA onto L-serine to yield O-acetyl-L-serine.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The following reaction step, catalyzed by the enzyme O-acetyl serine (thiol) lyase, replaces the acetyl group of O-acetyl-L-serine with sulfide to yield cysteine.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The aspartate family of amino acids includes: threonine, lysine, methionine, isoleucine, and aspartate.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Lysine and isoleucine are considered part of the aspartate family even though part of their carbon skeleton is derived from pyruvate.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] In the case of methionine, the methyl carbon is derived from serine and the sulfur group, but in most organisms, it is derived from cysteine.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The biosynthesis of aspartate is a one step reaction that is catalyzed by a single enzyme.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The enzyme aspartate aminotransferase catalyzes the transfer of an amino group from aspartate onto α-ketoglutarate to yield glutamate and oxaloacetate.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Asparagine is synthesized by an ATP-dependent addition of an amino group onto aspartate; asparagine synthetase catalyzes the addition of nitrogen from glutamine or soluble ammonia to aspartate to yield asparagine.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The diaminopimelic acid biosynthetic pathway of lysine belongs to the aspartate family of amino acids.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] This pathway involves nine enzyme-catalyzed reactions that convert aspartate to lysine.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Aspartate-semialdehyde dehydrogenase catalyzes the reduction reaction by dephosphorylation of aspartyl-β-phosphate to yield aspartate-β-semialdehyde.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Dihydrodipicolinate synthase catalyzes the condensation reaction of aspartate-β-semialdehyde with pyruvate to yield dihydrodipicolinic acid.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] 4-hydroxy-tetrahydrodipicolinate reductase catalyzes the reduction of dihydrodipicolinic acid to yield tetrahydrodipicolinic acid.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Tetrahydrodipicolinate N-succinyltransferase catalyzes the transfer of a succinyl group from succinyl-CoA on to tetrahydrodipicolinic acid to yield N-succinyl-L-2,6-diaminoheptanedioate.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] N-succinyldiaminopimelate aminotransferase catalyzes the transfer of an amino group from glutamate onto N-succinyl-L-2,6-diaminoheptanedioate to yield N-succinyl-L,L-diaminopimelic acid.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Succinyl-diaminopimelate desuccinylase catalyzes the removal of acyl group from N-succinyl-L,L-diaminopimelic acid to yield L,L-diaminopimelic acid.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Diaminopimelate epimerase catalyzes the inversion of the α-carbon of L,L-diaminopimelic acid to yield meso-diaminopimelic acid.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Siaminopimelate decarboxylase catalyzes the final step in lysine biosynthesis that removes the carbon dioxide group from meso-diaminopimelic acid to yield L-lysine.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Protein synthesis occurs via a process called translation.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] During translation, genetic material called mRNA is read by ribosomes to generate a protein polypeptide chain.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] This process requires transfer RNA (tRNA) which serves as an adaptor by binding amino acids on one end and interacting with mRNA at the other end; the latter pairing between the tRNA and mRNA ensures that the correct amino acid is added to the chain.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Protein synthesis occurs in three phases: initiation, elongation, and termination.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Prokaryotic (archaeal and bacterial) translation differs from eukaryotic translation; however, this section will mostly focus on the commonalities between the two organisms.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Before translation can begin, the process of binding a specific amino acid to its corresponding tRNA must occur.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] This reaction, called tRNA charging, is catalyzed by aminoacyl tRNA synthetase.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] A specific tRNA synthetase is responsible for recognizing and charging a particular amino acid.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Furthermore, this enzyme has special discriminator regions to ensure the correct binding between tRNA and its cognate amino acid.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] This is followed by the transfer of the aminoacyl group from aminoacyl-AMP to a tRNA molecule.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The combination of these two steps, both of which are catalyzed by aminoacyl tRNA synthetase, produces a charged tRNA that is ready to add amino acids to the growing polypeptide chain.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] In addition to binding an amino acid, tRNA has a three nucleotide unit called an anticodon that base pairs with specific nucleotide triplets on the mRNA called codons; codons encode a specific amino acid.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] This interaction is possible thanks to the ribosome, which serves as the site for protein synthesis.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The ribosome possesses three tRNA binding sites: the aminoacyl site (A site), the peptidyl site (P site), and the exit site (E site).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] There are numerous codons within an mRNA transcript, and it is very common for an amino acid to be specified by more than one codon; this phenomenon is called degeneracy.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] In all, there are 64 codons, 61 of each code for one of the 20 amino acids, while the remaining codons specify chain termination.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] As previously mentioned, translation occurs in three phases: initiation, elongation, and termination.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Following initiation, the polypeptide chain is extended via anticodon:codon interactions, with the ribosome adding amino acids to the polypeptide chain one at a time.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Translocation "kicks off" the tRNA at the E site and shifts the tRNA from the A site into the P site, leaving the A site free for an incoming tRNA to add another amino acid.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] The last stage of translation occurs when a stop codon enters the A site.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Errors in biosynthetic pathways can have deleterious consequences including the malformation of macromolecules or the underproduction of functional molecules.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/biosynthesis] Below are examples that illustrate the disruptions that occur due to these inefficiencies.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] Only two fatty acids are known to be essential for humans: alpha-linolenic acid (an omega−3 fatty acid) and linoleic acid (an omega−6 fatty acid).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] These are supplied to the body either as the free fatty acid, or more commonly as some glyceride derivative.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] ALA can be converted into eicosapentaenoic acid and docosahexaenoic acid, but the conversion amount is small, requiring intake from food or supplements.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] Deficiency in omega−3 fatty acids is very common.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] The average American has a dietary ratio between omega−6 fatty acids and omega−3 fatty acids of 20:1.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] When the two EFAs were discovered in 1923, they were designated "vitamin F", but in 1929, research on rats showed that the two EFAs are better classified as fats rather than vitamins.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] In the body, essential fatty acids serve multiple functions.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] In each of these, the balance between dietary ω−3 and ω−6 strongly affects function.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] Fatty acids comprise an aliphatic hydrocarbon chain plus a carboxyl group (–COOH) at one end, and terminated by a methyl group (–CH3) at the other end.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] They are almost always straight-chained.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] The carbon next to the carboxylate is known as α, the next carbon β, and so forth.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] Since biological fatty acids can be of diverse lengths, the last position is often labelled as "ω", the last letter in the Greek alphabet.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] In the expression *ω−x*, the minus symbol represents subtraction, indicating how many carbons away from the terminal end (ω) of the chain that the first unsaturated carbon-carbon bond appears.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] Typically, the number of carbons and the number of double bonds are also listed in short descriptions of unsaturated fatty acids.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] For instance, ω−3 18:4, or 18:4 ω−3, or 18:4 n−3 indicate stearidonic acid, an 18-carbon chain with 4 double bonds, and with a double bond between the third and fourth carbon atoms from the CH3 end.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] Double bonds are *cis* (on the same side of the double bond) and separated by a single methylene (CH2) group unless otherwise noted.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] Polyunsaturated fatty acids with 16- and 18-carbon chains are sometimes classified as **short chain polyunsaturated fatty acids** (**SC-PUFA**), as opposed to **long-chain polyunsaturated fatty acids** (**LC-PUFA**), which have more than 18 carbon atoms.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] These two fatty acids cannot be synthesized by humans because humans lack the desaturase enzymes required for their production.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] Except for GLA, which has a short 18-carbon chain, these fatty acids have more than 18 carbon atoms and are typically classified as LC-PUFA.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] ω−9 fatty acids are not essential in humans because they can be synthesized from carbohydrates or other fatty acids.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] Mammals lack the ability to introduce double bonds in fatty acids beyond carbon 9 and 10, hence the omega−6 linoleic acid (18:2n−6; LA) and the omega−3 alpha-linolenic acid (18:3n−3; ALA) are essential for humans in the diet.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] However, humans can convert both LA and ALA to fatty acids with longer carbon chains and a larger number of double bonds, by alternative desaturation and chain elongation.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] In humans, arachidonic acid (20:4n−6; AA) can be synthesized from LA.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] In turn, AA can be converted to an even longer fatty acid, the docosapentaenoic acid (22:5n−6; DPA).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] Similarly, ALA can be converted to docosahexaenoic acid (22:6n−3; DHA), although the latter conversion is limited, resulting in lower blood levels of DHA than through direct ingestion.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] This is illustrated by studies in vegans and vegetarians.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] If there is relatively more LA than ALA in the diet it favors the formation of DPA from LA rather than DHA from ALA.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] This effect can be altered by changing the relative ratio of LA:ALA, but is more effective when total intake of polyunsaturated fatty acids is low.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] In preterm infants, the capacity to convert LA to AA and ALA to DHA is limited, and preformed AA and DHA may be required to meet the needs of the developing brain.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] Both AA and DHA are present in breastmilk and contribute along with the parent fatty acids LA and ALA to meeting the requirements of the newborn infant.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] Many infant formulas have AA and DHA added to them with an aim to make them more equivalent to human milk.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] The main physiological requirement for ω−6 fatty acids is attributed to arachidonic acid, which is the major precursor of prostaglandins, leukotrienes that play a vital role in cell signaling, and an endogenous cannabinoid anandamide.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] Metabolites from the ω−3 pathway, mainly from eicosapentaenoic acid, are mostly inactive.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] Reviews by the European Food Safety Authority made recommendations for minimal intakes of LA and ALA and have also recommended intakes of longer chain ω−3 fatty acids based on the association of oily fish consumption with a lower risk of cardiovascular disease.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] Some of the food sources of ω−3 and ω−6 fatty acids are fish and shellfish, seaweed oil, flaxseed (linseed) and flaxseed oil, hemp seed, olive oil, soya oil, canola (rapeseed) oil, chia seeds, pumpkin seeds, sunflower seeds, leafy vegetables, and walnuts.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] Essential fatty acids play a part in many metabolic processes, and there is evidence to suggest that low levels of essential fatty acids, or the wrong balance of types among the essential fatty acids, may be a factor in a number of illnesses, including osteoporosis.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] Fish is the main source of the longer omega−3 fats; eicosapentaenoic acid (EPA) and docosahexaenoic acid (DHA), though they initially acquire these fats through the consumption of algae and seaweed.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] Some plant-based foods contain omega−3 in the form of alpha-linolenic acid (ALA), which appears to have a modest benefit for cardiovascular health.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] The human body can (and in case of a purely vegetarian diet often must unless certain algae or supplements derived from them are consumed) convert ALA to EPA and subsequently DHA.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] The conversion of ALA to DHA is sufficient in the adult and additional DHA is not required in the diet.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] In the infant, the case is less clear; preformed DHA may be required in breastmilk or formula for adequate development, as DHA supplementation in formula was found to improve cognitive development up to one year of age.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] The effects of DHA supplementation in early childhood after one year are unclear.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] The *IUPAC Lipid Handbook* provides a very large and detailed listing of fat contents of animal and vegetable fats, including ω−3 and −6 oils.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] The National Institutes of Health's EFA Education group publishes *Essential Fats in Food Oils*.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] This lists 40 common oils, more tightly focused on EFAs and sorted by n−6:3 ratio.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] *Vegetable Lipids as Components of Functional Food* lists notable vegetable sources of EFAs as well as commentary and an overview of the biosynthetic pathways involved.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] However, these sources are not in perfect agreement.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] EFA content of vegetable sources varies with cultivation conditions.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] Animal sources vary widely, both with the animal's feed and that the EFA makeup varies markedly with fats from different body parts.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] Essential fatty acids play an important role in the life and death of cardiac cells.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] Additionally, essential fatty acids are crucial for the development of several endocannabinoids with a multitude of functions in the body, such as docosahexaenoyl ethanolamide (DHA-EA/synaptamide).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] Reference intake values for as published by the Panel on Dietetic Products, Nutrition and Allergies of the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA).
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] In the United States, the Adequate Intake (AI) for omega−3 fatty acids is for ALA.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] It is based on the median intake, and for adults the values are 1.6 g/day for men and 1.1 g/day for women.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] EPA and DHA contribute about 10 percent of total omega−3 intake.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] The AI for omega−6 fatty acids is for linoleic acid and is also based on the median intake: 17 g/day for younger men, dropping to 14 g/day for men over 50 years old; for younger women 12 g/d, and 11 g/day for women over 50.
[src:essential-fatty-acid/essential-fatty-acid] Studies have shown that smaller intakes reverse the symptoms of deficiency, but there is inadequate information to set an Estimated Average Requirement (EAR) for either.
